tion in Virginia''' was held on November 5, 2002. Incumbent Republican U.S. Senator [[John Warner]] won re-election to a fifth term, making him one of only three Virginia U.S. Senators to serve five or more terms.<ref>http://search.proquest.com/docview/423821298</ref> The [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] did not field a candidate against Warner, and he won every single county and city in the state with at least 60% of the vote. As of {{CURRENTYEAR}}, this is the last Senate election in Virginia won by a Republican.\n\n== Major candidates ==\n\n=== Independents ===\n* [[Jacob Hornberger]], [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]] political activist\n* Nancy Spannaus, [[Lyndon LaRouche Movement]] activist<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4C0zAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RggGAAAAIBAJ&pg=6707,595341&dq=nancy%20spannaus&hl=en \"The Free Lance-Star - Google News Archive Search\"]. </ref>\n\n=== Republican ===\n* [[John Warner]], incumbent U.S. Senator\n\n== Results ==\n{{Election box begin\n | title      = United States Senate election in Virginia, 2002<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/2002/2002Stat.htm#46 \"2002 ELECTION STATISTICS\"]. </ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n | party      = Republican Party (United States)\n | candidate  = [[John Warner]] (incumbent)\n | votes      = 1,229,894\n | percentage = 82.58%\n | change     = +30.10%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n | party      = Independent (United States)\n | candidate  = Nancy B. Spannaus\n | votes      = 145,102\n | percentage = 9.74%\n | change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n | party      = Independent (United States)\n | candidate  = [[Jacob Hornberger]]\n | votes      = 106,055\n | percentage = 7.12%\n | change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n | party      = Write-ins\n | candidate  = \n | votes      = 8,371\n | percentage = 0.56%\n | change     = +0.43%\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n | votes      = 1,0