{"title_page": "Specula Melitensis Encyclica", "text_new": "[[File:Title page of \u201cSpecula Melitensis Encyclica\u201d.jpg|thumb|Title page of \u201cSpecula Melitensis Encyclica\u201d]]\n'''''Specula Melitensis Encyclica''''' (\u201cThe Maltese Observatory\u201d or \u201cThe Circular Maltese Mirror\u201d)<ref name=\"EB\">{{cite journal |last1=Buttigieg |first1=Emanuel |title=KNIGHTS, JESUITS, CARNIVAL, AND THE INQUISITION IN SEVENTEENTH-CENTURY MALTA |journal=The Historical Journal |date=September 2012 |volume=55 |issue=3 |page=572 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23263265?read-now=1&loggedin=true |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> was a 1638 work by the [[Jesuit]] scholar [[Athanasius Kircher]]. It was printed in Naples by Secundino Roncagliolo<ref>{{cite book|author=Harold B. Lee Library|title=Athanasius Kircher (1602-1680), Jesuit Scholar: An Exhibition of His Works in the Harold B. Lee Library Collections at Brigham Young University|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=29984eQF86UC&pg=PR33|year=2003|publisher=Martino Publishing|isbn=978-1-57898-432-9|page=xxxiii}}</ref> and dedicated to [[Giovanni Paolo Lascaris]], [[Grand Master]] of the [[Knights of Malta]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kircher |first1=Athanasius |title=Specula Melitensis encyclica |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_BAO1uGDc4twC/page/n1/mode/2up |website=archive.org |publisher=archive.org |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe work described an instrument that Kircher had built while on a trip to [[Malta]] as the confessor of [[Frederick of Hesse-Darmstadt|Friedrich of Hesse-Darmstadt]]. This instrument, which he called the Specula Melitensis, was a [[mechanical calculator]] that included a planisphere, a means of counting both the Julian and Gregorian calendars, charted horoscopes, and condensed all important medical, botanical, alchemical, hermetic knowledge into a single cube known as the \u201ccabalistic mirror.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Findlen |first1=Paula |title=Kircher, Athanasius |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/people/science-and-technology/mathematics-biographies/athanasius-kircher |website=encyclopaedia.com |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Barth\u00e9lemy Mercier de Saint-L\u00e9ger|title=Notice raisonn\u00e9e des ouvrages de Gaspar Schott: contenant des Observations curieuses sur la Physique Exp\u00e9rimentale, l'Histoire Naturelle & les Arts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DdBIAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA55|accessdate=12 April 2020|year=1785|publisher=Lagrange|page=55}}</ref> Altogether this instrument had 125 distinct uses.<ref name=\"EB\"/>\n\nUnusually for works by Kircher, this book acknowledged a collaborator, the Maltese historian and prior of St John\u2019s, Salvatore Imbroll, who seems to have completed the project with material begun by Kircher.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Freller |first1=Thomas |title=Olaf Hein Die Drucker und Verleger der Werke des Polyhistors Athanasius Kircher S.J |url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.13(2000-03)/MH.13(2000)1/07.pdf |website=melitensiawth.com |publisher=Melita Historica : A Scientific Review of Maltese History. |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe calculator described in the work was later than machines devised by [[Napier's bones|John Napier]] and [[Wilhelm Schickard]], but earlier than that of [[Pascal's calculator|Blaise Pascal]]. \n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_BAO1uGDc4twC/mode/2up digital copy of Specula Melitensis Encyclica]\n\n==Reference==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1638 in science]]\n[[Category:1638 works]]\n[[Category:Calculators]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Title page of \u201cSpecula Melitensis Encyclica\u201d.jpg|thumb|Title page of \u201cSpecula Melitensis Encyclica\u201d]]\n'''''Specula Melitensis Encyclica''''' (\u201cThe Maltese Observatory\u201d or \u201cThe Circular Maltese Mirror\u201d)<ref name=\"EB\">{{cite journal |last1=Buttigieg |first1=Emanuel |title=KNIGHTS, JESUITS, CARNIVAL, AND THE INQUISITION IN SEVENTEENTH-CENTURY MALTA |journal=The Historical Journal |date=September 2012 |volume=55 |issue=3 |page=572 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23263265?read-now=1&loggedin=true |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> was a 1638 work by the [[Jesuit]] scholar [[Athanasius Kircher]]. It was printed in Naples by Secundino Roncagliolo<ref>{{cite book|author=Harold B. Lee Library|title=Athanasius Kircher (1602-1680), Jesuit Scholar: An Exhibition of His Works in the Harold B. Lee Library Collections at Brigham Young University|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=29984eQF86UC&pg=PR33|year=2003|publisher=Martino Publishing|isbn=978-1-57898-432-9|page=xxxiii}}</ref> and dedicated to [[Giovanni Paolo Lascaris]], [[Grand Master]] of the [[Knights of Malta]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kircher |first1=Athanasius |title=Specula Melitensis encyclica |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_BAO1uGDc4twC/page/n1/mode/2up |website=archive.org |publisher=archive.org |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe work described an instrument that Kircher had built while on a trip to [[Malta]] as the confessor of [[Frederick of Hesse-Darmstadt|Friedrich of Hesse-Darmstadt]]. This instrument, which he called the Specula Melitensis, was a [[mechanical calculator]] that included a planisphere, a means of counting both the Julian and Gregorian calendars, charted horoscopes, and condensed all important medical, botanical, alchemical, hermetic knowledge into a single cube known as the \u201ccabalistic mirror.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Findlen |first1=Paula |title=Kircher, Athanasius |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/people/science-and-technology/mathematics-biographies/athanasius-kircher |website=encyclopaedia.com |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Barth\u00e9lemy Mercier de Saint-L\u00e9ger|title=Notice raisonn\u00e9e des ouvrages de Gaspar Schott: contenant des Observations curieuses sur la Physique Exp\u00e9rimentale, l'Histoire Naturelle & les Arts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DdBIAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA55|accessdate=12 April 2020|year=1785|publisher=Lagrange|page=55}}</ref> Altogether this instrument had 125 distinct uses.<ref name=\"EB\"/>\n\nUnusually for works by Kircher, this book acknowledged a collaborator, the Maltese historian and prior of St John\u2019s, Salvatore Imbroll, who seems to have completed the project with material begun by Kircher.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Freller |first1=Thomas |title=Olaf Hein Die Drucker und Verleger der Werke des Polyhistors Athanasius Kircher S.J |url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.13(2000-03)/MH.13(2000)1/07.pdf |website=melitensiawth.com |publisher=Melita Historica : A Scientific Review of Maltese History. |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe calculator described in the work was later than machines devised by [[Napier's bones|John Napier]] and [[Wilhelm Schickard]], but earlier than that of [[Pascal's calculator|Blaise Pascal]]. \n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_BAO1uGDc4twC/mode/2up digital copy of Specula Melitensis Encyclica]\n\n==Reference==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1638 in science]]\n[[Category:1638 works]]\n[[Ctegory:Calculators]]\n", "name_user": "Mccapra", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Specula_Melitensis_Encyclica"}
